		<div class="site-content" data-off-canvas-content>
<div class="grid-container grid-x">
	<div class="cell large-8 small-12 main-content-well">
		<div class="story-content">
							<div class="story-info">
	<div class="featured-img-container">
		<img class="story-img" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-726x400.jpeg" title="Thomas Pynchon, Marisa Meltzer, Chris Kraus, and more: 24 new books out today!">
			</div>
	<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>Thomas Pynchon, Marisa Meltzer, Chris Kraus, and more: 24 new books out today!</h1>
			</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/juliahass/"  title="Julia Hass">Julia Hass</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">October 7, 2025</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p style="text-align: left;">The clock struck October, and with it, we welcomed in a slew of meaty, fascinating, and binge-worthy books. At long last, Thomas Pynchon&#8217;s <em>Shadow Ticket,</em> a much-anticipated work by the 88-year-old author is released. In other fiction news, there&#8217;s a radically new take on the murder-in-a-small-town genre by Chris Kraus, fresh, unusual stories by Katherine Dunn, and a tear-jerker by Mitch Albom, among many others.</p>
<p>And there&#8217;s no shortage of options for our nonfiction readers: there are biographies, autobiographies, and analyses on Gertrude Stein, Taylor Swift, Yusuf/Cat Stevens, and Joy Harjo. There are a couple incisive books that take on the dismal state of our digital age, by Cory Doctorow and Paul Leonardi. And in true, spooky October fashion, there&#8217;s a new work of nonfiction by Coltan Scrivener that explains the culture&#8217;s fascination with all things horror.</p>
<p>For me, Chris Kraus, Daniel H. Wilson, and Brenda Lozano are calling my name. Happy October, and happy reading!</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260410" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/attachment/9781594206108/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108.jpeg" data-orig-size="296,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Shadow Ticket, Thomas Pynchon" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260410" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108-197x300.jpeg" alt="Shadow Ticket, Thomas Pynchon" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781594206108.jpeg 296w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Thomas Pynchon, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781594206108" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Shadow Ticket</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Penguin Press)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Rollicking, genially silly and ultimately sweet &#8230; Pynchon’s prose is&#8230;balletically dazzling.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Washington Post</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255936" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71affsyrltl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="652,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Marisa Meltzer, It Girl: The Life and Legacy of Jane Birkin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255936" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg" alt="Marisa Meltzer, It Girl: The Life and Legacy of Jane Birkin" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71AffSyRLTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 652w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Marisa Meltzer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781668060285" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>It Girl: The Life and Legacy of Jane Birkin</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Atria)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Captures the rawness of Birkin’s life and the contradictions of a woman who was making things up as she went along.&#8221;<br />
—<em>W Magazine</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255926" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2146" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Chris Kraus, The Four Spent the Day Together" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-668x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255926" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-196x300.jpg" alt="Chris Kraus, The Four Spent the Day Together" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-768x1177.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-1002x1536.jpg 1002w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-1336x2048.jpg 1336w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-four-spent-the-day-together-9781668098684_hr.jpg 1400w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Chris Kraus, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781668098684" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Four Spent the Day Together</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Scribner)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;This is an entirely new kind of novel, one that shows how helplessly connected we are to our time and to each other. It&#8217;s rich, heartbreaking and powerful.”<br />
—Eileen Myles</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255942" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71vzupjeckl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Cory Doctorow, Enshittification: Why Everything Suddenly Got Worse and What to Do About It" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255942" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Cory Doctorow, Enshittification: Why Everything Suddenly Got Worse and What to Do About It" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71vzuPJecKL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Cory Doctorow, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780374619329" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Enshittification</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(MCD)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A razor-sharp yet subtly optimistic look at the soul-sucking state of the internet.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255924" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9780374602352/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2531" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Katherine Dunn, Near Flesh: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-668x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255924" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-196x300.jpg" alt="Katherine Dunn, Near Flesh: Stories" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-1001x1536.jpg 1001w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-1335x2048.jpg 1335w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352.jpg 1650w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Katherine Dunn, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780374602352" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Near Flesh: Stories</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(MCD)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“Delightfully offbeat &#8230; Dunn vividly captures her protagonists’ attempts to cope with the turbulence of their lives.”<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260412" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/81cxwgpzdil-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="666,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Cat on the Road to Find out, Cat Stevens" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260412" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Cat on the Road to Find out, Cat Stevens" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81cXWgpZDIL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 666w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
