<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jon Fosse, trans. by Damion Searls, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9798893380217" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Vaim</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Transit)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Fosse centers this spectacular story of loneliness, love, and death on three linked characters living in small-town Norway &#8230; This is unforgettable.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260727" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/erpenbeck-things-that-disappear-rgb/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1660,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Things That Disappear, Jenny Erpenbeck" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-664x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260727 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-195x300.jpg" alt="Things That Disappear, Jenny Erpenbeck" width="195" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-768x1184.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-996x1536.jpg 996w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-1328x2048.jpg 1328w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Erpenbeck-THINGS-THAT-DISAPPEAR-rgb-scaled.jpg 1660w" sizes="(max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jenny Erpenbeck, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780811238113" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Things That Disappear</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(New Directions)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;An ethereal collection of memories, delicately rendered before their inevitable crumbling away &#8230; A wistful record of memory and loss. Ephemeral musings, both peculiar and poetic.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255941" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81r1nzhhtyl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Beth Macy, Paper Girl: A Memoir of Home and Family in a Fractured America" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255941" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" alt="Beth Macy, Paper Girl: A Memoir of Home and Family in a Fractured America" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81R1nzHHTYL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 658w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Beth Macy, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593656730" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Paper Girl: A Memoir of Home and Family in a Fractured America</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Penguin Press)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Both wide-ranging and strikingly intimate, <em>Paper Girl</em> is an affirmation of faith in human­ity, and Macy lights the way ahead, even as the darkness stretched before us threatens to swallow our conviction.”<br />
—<em>BookPage</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260417" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/81jzug2ttl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Digital Exhaustion, Paul Leonardi" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260417" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Digital Exhaustion, Paul Leonardi" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81jZUg2tTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Paul Leonardi, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593851234" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Digital Exhaustion: Simple Rules for Reclaiming Your Life</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Riverhead)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“An invitation to think more deeply about the ways in which we interact with our devices.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260423" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/81i2wvbol-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="689,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mitch Albom, Twice" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_-207x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260423" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_-207x300.jpg" alt="Mitch Albom, Twice" width="207" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_-207x300.jpg 207w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81I2WVBoL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 689w" sizes="(max-width: 207px) 100vw, 207px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Mitch Albom, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780062406682" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Twice</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Harper)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Albom writes in a warm, easy style that transports the reader to a world of second chances and what-ifs, where spirituality lies close to the surface but never intrudes on the story &#8230; Have tissues ready as you read this.”<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260420" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/71g7s-1yizl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="661,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Last Supper, Sam Kass" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260420" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" alt="The Last Supper, Sam Kass" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71g7S-1YIZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 661w" sizes="(max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sam Kass, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780451494962" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Last Supper: How to Overcome the Coming Food Crisis</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Crown)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“Smart, timely, and full of purpose.”<br />
—Michelle Obama</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260429" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/attachment/225819299/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299.jpeg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="And I&#8217;ll Take Out Your Eyes, AM Sosa" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-679x1024.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260429" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-199x300.jpeg" alt="And I'll Take Out Your Eyes, AM Sosa " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-679x1024.jpeg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-768x1159.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/225819299.jpeg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>A M Sosa, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781643756912" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>And I&#8217;ll Take Out Your Eyes</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Algonquin)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;An insultingly good debut from a writer I&#8217;ll follow forever. <em>And I&#8217;ll Take Out Your Eyes</em> is a poetic gut punch that heals just as much as it haunts.&#8221;<br />
—Ruth Madievsky</p>
