<strong>(Atria)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“A riveting story with a master&#8217;s sublime command. There are moments when this work of non-fiction seems more like a novel. It is taut, suspenseful, and true. I couldn&#8217;t put it down.”<br />
—Ken Burns</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255937" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9780143137344/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344.jpg" data-orig-size="299,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Coltan Scrivner, Morbidly Curious" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255937" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344-199x300.jpg" alt="Coltan Scrivner, Morbidly Curious" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780143137344.jpg 299w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Coltan Scrivner, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780143137344" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Morbidly Curious: A Scientist Explains Why We Can&#8217;t Look Away</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Penguin Books)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“A remarkable journey that delves into why humans can’t seem to look away from the things that some would refer to as unhealthy, shocking, or fearsome.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Library Journal</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255929" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9781646222537-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Brenda Lozano, tr. Heather Cleary, Mothers" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255929" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy-199x300.jpg" alt="Brenda Lozano, tr. Heather Cleary, Mothers" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222537-copy.jpg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Brenda Lozano, trans. by Heather Cleary, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781646222537" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Mothers</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Catapult)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Brenda Lozano has written a powerful and haunting tale, full of twists and surprises, but also incisive observations on what it means to be a woman and a mother—both in 1940s Mexico and in the world today.&#8221;<br />
—Miriam Toews</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255939" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2146" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Francesca Wade, Gertrude Stein: An Afterlife" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-668x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255939" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-196x300.jpg" alt="Francesca Wade, Gertrude Stein: An Afterlife" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-768x1177.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-1002x1536.jpg 1002w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-1336x2048.jpg 1336w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/gertrude-stein-9781982186012_hr.jpg 1400w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Francesca Wade, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781982186012" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Gertrude Stein: An Afterlife</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Scribner)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Wade on Stein is a perfect miracle. I feel like I have been waiting for this book my entire life.&#8221;<br />
—Sheila Heti</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260431" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/thomas-pynchon-marisa-meltzer-chris-kraus-and-more-24-new-books-out-today/screen-shot-2025-09-29-at-12-20-31-pm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM.png" data-orig-size="944,1450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sea, Poison, Caren Beilin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-195x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-667x1024.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-260431" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-195x300.png" alt="Sea, Poison, Caren Beilin" width="195" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-195x300.png 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-667x1024.png 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-768x1180.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM-33x50.png 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-29-at-12.20.31-PM.png 944w" sizes="(max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Caren Beilin, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780811239516" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Sea, Poison</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(New Directions)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;This rewarding and uncompromising novel is distinguished by its deliriously wild writing. It&#8217;s impossible not to be swept up in Beilin&#8217;s wake.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255938" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9781324094173/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173.jpg" data-orig-size="267,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Joy Harjo, Girl Warrior: On Coming of Age" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255938" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173-200x300.jpg" alt="Joy Harjo, Girl Warrior: On Coming of Age" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781324094173.jpg 267w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Joy Harjo, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781324094173" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Girl Warrior: On Coming of Age</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(W. W. Norton)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;More than about having waded through tumultuous waters and survived to not only tell the story but thrive inside the people we become on the other side. This book is simply a balm.&#8221;<br />
—Jacqueline Woodson</p>
